i## title: My homelab	/	tilde.team	70
i## date: "2024-06-06"	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI've got an old laptop that I don't use anymore, so I	/	tilde.team	70
ithought I'd turn it into a server and deploy some free, open-	/	tilde.team	70
isource web services on it.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThe aim is to create a private homelab, i.e. the machine	/	tilde.team	70
ishould only be accessible via the local network. None of the	/	tilde.team	70
iservices are exposed to the Internet, with the exception of	/	tilde.team	70
iWireguard, which lets me access the services from the	/	tilde.team	70
ioutside.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThe aim of this post is to present the main steps I've taken	/	tilde.team	70
iand explain how the homelab works.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iMy laptop is an ASUS ROG G750 with 8GB of memory and 2 HDDs	/	tilde.team	70
iof around 600GB each. It hasn't been used for about five or	/	tilde.team	70
isix years and the battery is dead.	/	tilde.team	70
hASUS ROG G750	URL:https://laptopmedia.com/series/asus-rog-g750/	laptopmedia.com	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## First steps	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iFirst, I decided to make an old USB key bootable. I install	/	tilde.team	70
iVentoy on it to be able to load different image disks (ISO)	/	tilde.team	70
iwithout having to rewrite each time directly on the USB key.	/	tilde.team	70
hVentoy	URL:https://www.ventoy.net/	www.ventoy.net	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI put Memtest86+ to test the memory, shredos.x86_64 to wipe	/	tilde.team	70
ithe HDDs and finally Debian 12 which will be the main OS.	/	tilde.team	70
hMemtest86+	URL:https://www.memtest.org/	www.memtest.org	443
hshredos.x86_64	URL:https://github.com/PartialVolume/shredos.x86_64	github.com	443
hDebian 12	URL:https://cdimage.debian.org/debian-cd/12.5.0/amd64/iso-cd/	cdimage.debian.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iSo when I boot on the USB key, it loads the "multiboot" boot-	/	tilde.team	70
iloader (Ventoy) and I can then load one of the three	/	tilde.team	70
iprograms.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## Pre configuration	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iTo be able to deploy the system configuration and reproduce	/	tilde.team	70
iit later, I'm writing an Ansible playbook and testing it on	/	tilde.team	70
ia local VM (virt-manager + KVM).	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThe entire configuration is available at the bottom of the	/	tilde.team	70
ipage.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## TLS certificates	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI want communication with web applications to be encrypted	/	tilde.team	70
iand secure, so I need an HTTPS server, so I need TLS	/	tilde.team	70
icertificates and, to make things easier, a domain name.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iFor the domain name I used Duck DNS and reserved the sub-	/	tilde.team	70
idomain theobori.duckdns.org which for the moment corresponds	/	tilde.team	70
ito the IPv4 of my virtual machine accessible only from the	/	tilde.team	70
ihost system.	/	tilde.team	70
hDuck DNS	URL:https://www.duckdns.org/	www.duckdns.org	443
htheobori.duckdns.org	URL:https://theobori.duckdns.org	theobori.duckdns.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iIn fact, I only need to manage one certificate with two	/	tilde.team	70
iSANs:	/	tilde.team	70
i- theobori.duckdns.org	/	tilde.team	70
i- *.theobori.duckdns.org	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## Services	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iEvery application is deployed with the Ansible playbook are	/	tilde.team	70
iconteuneurized and managed with Docker.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThey are accessible only through port 443 managed by	/	tilde.team	70
iTraefik. Each sub-domain of theobori.duckdns.org corresponds	/	tilde.team	70
ito a service, with the exception of the homepage, which is	/	tilde.team	70
iassociated with the domain itself.	/	tilde.team	70
hTraefik	URL:https://traefik.io/	traefik.io	443
htheobori.duckdns.org	URL:https://theobori.duckdns.org	theobori.duckdns.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## Firewall	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iTo filter incoming network traffic, I manipulate iptables	/	tilde.team	70
iwith the ufw tool. There are only four ports open as	/	tilde.team	70
ideclared below in the Ansible playbook configuration.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i- role: weareinteractive.ufw	/	tilde.team	70
i  tags: ufw	/	tilde.team	70
i  ufw_enabled: true	/	tilde.team	70
i  ufw_packages: ["ufw"]	/	tilde.team	70
i  ufw_rules:	/	tilde.team	70
i  - logging: "full"	/	tilde.team	70
i  - rule: allow	/	tilde.team	70
i      to_port: "443"	/	tilde.team	70
i  - rule: allow	/	tilde.team	70
i      to_port: "80"	/	tilde.team	70
i  - rule: allow	/	tilde.team	70
i    {% raw %} to_port: "{{ ssh_port }}" {% endraw %}	/	tilde.team	70
i  # Wireguard	/	tilde.team	70
i  - rule: allow	/	tilde.team	70
i      to_port: "51820"	/	tilde.team	70
i      proto: udp	/	tilde.team	70
i  # Delete default rule	/	tilde.team	70
i  - rule: allow	/	tilde.team	70
i      name: Anywhere	/	tilde.team	70
i      delete: true	/	tilde.team	70
i  ufw_manage_config: true	/	tilde.team	70
i  ufw_config:	/	tilde.team	70
i  IPV6: "yes"	/	tilde.team	70
i  DEFAULT_INPUT_POLICY: DROP	/	tilde.team	70
i  DEFAULT_OUTPUT_POLICY: ACCEPT	/	tilde.team	70
i  DEFAULT_FORWARD_POLICY: DROP	/	tilde.team	70
i  DEFAULT_APPLICATION_POLICY: SKIP	/	tilde.team	70
i  MANAGE_BUILTINS: "no"	/	tilde.team	70
i  IPT_SYSCTL: /etc/ufw/sysctl.conf	/	tilde.team	70
i  IPT_MODULES: ""	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## Identity provider	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iServices with integration for protocols to verify user	/	tilde.team	70
iidentity or determine permissions are all linked to the	/	tilde.team	70
iAuthentik user directory.	/	tilde.team	70
hAuthentik	URL:https://goauthentik.io/	goauthentik.io	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI needed OAuth2 for Portainer and LDAP for several other	/	tilde.team	70
iservices such as Owncloud.	/	tilde.team	70
hPortainer	URL:https://www.portainer.io/	www.portainer.io	443
hOwncloud	URL:https://owncloud.com/	owncloud.com	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iIf I remember correctly, the OAuth2 Outpost is embedded in	/	tilde.team	70
ithe application by default, whereas the LDAP Outpost had to	/	tilde.team	70
ibe configured with specific parameters for Docker.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iHere's a diagram of several services trying to retrieve the	/	tilde.team	70
iidentity of an Authentik user.	/	tilde.team	70
hAuthentik	URL:https://goauthentik.io/	goauthentik.io	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
i/authentik_users.png	/	tilde.team	70
I/authentik_users.png	/~nagi/authentik_users.png	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## Access management	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iWith Authentik, group policies have been created to	/	tilde.team	70
iauthorize only certain groups of users to access certain	/	tilde.team	70
iservices.	/	tilde.team	70
hAuthentik	URL:https://goauthentik.io/	goauthentik.io	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iFor example, for Jellyfin, only users in the Jellyfin group	/	tilde.team	70
iare authorized to connect.	/	tilde.team	70
hJellyfin	URL:https://jellyfin.org/	jellyfin.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iIn this way, I was able to secure all administration	/	tilde.team	70
iservices by authorizing only users in groups reserved for	/	tilde.team	70
iadministration.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI also used Traefik and Authentik to secure access to	/	tilde.team	70
iservices not protected by authentication.	/	tilde.team	70
hTraefik	URL:https://traefik.io/	traefik.io	443
hAuthentik	URL:https://goauthentik.io/	goauthentik.io	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI added middleware to the reverse proxy to enable HTTP	/	tilde.team	70
iForwardAuth with Authentik. In practical terms, this places	/	tilde.team	70
ia connection portal in front of the targeted web services.	/	tilde.team	70
hAuthentik	URL:https://goauthentik.io/	goauthentik.io	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iLet's say I want to access duplicati.theobori.duckdns.org,	/	tilde.team	70
iit could be schematized as follows.	/	tilde.team	70
hduplicati.theobori.duckdns.org	URL:https://duplicati.theobori.duckdns.org	duplicati.theobori.duckdns.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
i/authentik_proxy.png	/	tilde.team	70
I/authentik_proxy.png	/~nagi/authentik_proxy.png	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## Media stack	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iOne of the main objectives was to be able to manage movies	/	tilde.team	70
iand series and watch them from any device on the local	/	tilde.team	70
inetwork.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iSo I set up a stack for managing and downloading media,	/	tilde.team	70
iwhich would then be streamed to devices by Jellyfin.	/	tilde.team	70
hJellyfin	URL:https://jellyfin.org/	jellyfin.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iHere's what the media stack looks like.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i/media_stack.png	/	tilde.team	70
